<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-02-20T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-02-20T04:00:00-05:00" n="10" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d10">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A12/41: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bancroft</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-02-20T18:00:00+09:00"><hi rend="italic">February 20,
                                        1925—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>34. My 33, February 20, 4 p.m.<note n="13" xml:id="d10fn13">Not
                                printed.</note> Have just seen United Press cablegram that President
                            Coolidge has received consent of England, Japan and Italy and is waiting
                            for consent of France before calling disarmament conference.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bancroft</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>